{
  id:6, topic:"Utility",
  text:"David has a budget of $30. Coffee is $2/cup, Donuts are $5 each. Which bundle maximizes his utility?",
  table:{headers:["Qty","TU Coffee","MU Coffee","TU Donuts","MU Donuts"],rows:[["1","12","12","25","25"],["2","22","10","45","20"],["3","30","8","60","15"],["4","36","6","70","10"],["5","40","4","75","5"]]},
  opts:["2 cups of Coffee and 5 Donuts","4 cups of Coffee and 4 donuts","4 cups of Coffee and 3 donuts","5 cups of Coffee and 4 donuts"],
  answer:3,
  explain:"Utility maximization rule: MU/P must be equal across goods. Check 5 Coffee + 4 Donuts: Cost = 5×$2 + 4×$5 = $30 ✓. MU_C(5)/P_C = 4/2 = 2. MU_D(4)/P_D = 10/5 = 2. They're EQUAL! That's the sweet spot.",
  catMsg:"Niko says: Always get the most bang for your treats... I mean bucks! 🐈"
},
{
  id:7, topic:"Utility",
  text:"Emily has $20 for Books ($4) and Movies ($2). She maximizes utility by equalizing MU per dollar. If Books rise to $5 while Movies stay at $2, what happens to Emily's purchases?",
  opts:["Emily will buy more Books and fewer Movies","Emily will buy the same amount of both","Emily will buy fewer Books and more Movies","Emily will buy fewer Movies and keep the same number of Books"],
  answer:2,
  explain:"When Books get more expensive, MU_Books/P_Books falls below MU_Movies/P_Movies. Emily shifts spending toward Movies (better value) and away from Books. This is the substitution effect in action!",
  catMsg:"Pie Cookie says: When the fancy cat food gets expensive, even I switch to the regular stuff. Smart shopping! 🐱"
},
{
  id:8, topic:"Trade",
  text:"Jane owns a small bookstore. Revenue was $100,000. She paid $60,000 for rent, wages, and operating expenses. If she could have earned $30,000 working elsewhere, what was her economic profit last year?",
  opts:["$10,0000","$10,000","$60,000","$40,000"],
  answer:1,
  explain:"Economic Profit = Revenue − Explicit Costs − Implicit Costs = $100,000 − $60,000 − $30,000 = $10,000. The $30,000 opportunity cost (what she COULD have earned elsewhere) must be subtracted. Accounting profit would be $40,000, but economists count what you give up!",
  catMsg:"Niko says: Opportunity cost is like choosing between the sunny window and the warm laundry — you always give up one! 🐈"
},
{
  id:9, topic:"Trade",
  text:"South Korea produces 5 Tablets or 15 Smartphones. The US produces 15 Tablets or 20 Smartphones. Following comparative advantage, which terms of trade are both available and best for the U.S.?",
  table:{headers:["","Tablets","Smart Phones"],rows:[["South Korea","5","15"],["United States","15","20"]]},
  opts:["1/4 Tablets per Smart Phone","1/2 Tablets per Smart Phone","1 Smart Phone per Tablet","3/4 Smart Phones per Tablet"],
  answer:1,
  explain:"US opp cost: 1 Tablet = 20/15 = 4/3 SP → US has comparative advantage in Tablets. For trade to work, terms must be between each country's opp costs. For SP: between 1/3 and 3/4 Tablets per SP. 1/2 falls in this range and gives the US the best deal!",
  catMsg:"Pie Cookie says: Trade is like sharing — I bring you a mouse, you give me treats. Everyone wins! 🐱"
},
{
  id:10, topic:"Trade",
  text:"Ann: 100 legal cases/yr or 20 chairs/yr. Bob: 90 legal cases/yr or 22 chairs/yr. Who has comparative advantage in providing legal services?",
  opts:["Ann","Bob","None","Both"],
  answer:0,
  explain:"Opp cost of 1 legal case: Ann = 20/100 = 0.2 chairs. Bob = 22/90 = 0.244 chairs. Ann gives up FEWER chairs per legal case, so Ann has comparative advantage in legal services. Bob has comparative advantage in making chairs!",
  catMsg:"Niko says: I have a comparative advantage in napping. Nobody naps better per unit of effort than me! 🐈"
},
{
  id:11, topic:"Trade",
  text:"Green line = international price (world supply), blue = domestic demand, red = domestic supply. If a free trade policy is implemented, which area represents the gains from trade?",
  opts:["E","F−E","C+D+E+F","A+B"],
  answer:0,
  explain:"When the world price is below the domestic equilibrium price, consumers benefit from cheaper imports. The net gain from trade is area E — the triangle representing additional consumer surplus that wasn't available under autarky (no trade).",
  catMsg:"Pie Cookie says: Free trade is like when both cats get to share the sunny spot — more happiness for everyone! 🐱"
},
{
  id:12, topic:"Trade",
  text:"Country originally in free trade at world price $5 (S and D are domestic). What is the transfer from consumer surplus to producer surplus if a quota is imposed that allows NO imports?",
  opts:["A+B+C+D+E+F","C+D","A+B","G"],
  answer:1,
  explain:"When a total import ban (quota = 0) is imposed, the price rises from the world price to the domestic equilibrium. Area C+D transfers from consumers to domestic producers. Areas representing deadweight loss (like B and E area) are lost entirely — nobody gets them.",
  catMsg:"Niko says: A quota is like when someone blocks the cat door — the inside cats win, but overall there's less happiness! 🐈"
},
{
  id:13, topic:"Trade",
  text:"The U.S. imposes a tariff on avocados from Mexico. Based on the domestic supply/demand graph showing world price rising from ~$12.50 to ~$15, what happens?",
  opts:["Both U.S. and Mexican avocado prices increase, imports from Mexico decrease","U.S. avocado price decreases, imports from Mexico increase","Mexican avocado price decreases, imports increase","U.S. avocado price stays the same, no change in imports"],
  answer:0,
  explain:"A tariff raises the effective price of imports. ALL avocado prices rise (domestic and imported). At higher prices: domestic supply increases, domestic demand decreases, so imports FALL. Tariffs always reduce imports and raise prices.",
  catMsg:"Pie Cookie says: Tariffs are like putting a toll on the cat flap — fewer visitors come through and everything costs more! 🐱"
},
{
  id:14, topic:"Elasticity",
  text:"Concert ticket price increases from $50 to $70, tickets sold drops from 1,000 to 800. Using the midpoint formula, what is the price elasticity of demand?",
  opts:["-0.66","-0.25","-1.5","-0.5"],
  answer:0,
  explain:"Midpoint formula: Ed = [(%ΔQ) / (%ΔP)]. %ΔQ = (800−1000)/((800+1000)/2) = −200/900 = −22.2%. %ΔP = (70−50)/((70+50)/2) = 20/60 = 33.3%. Ed = −22.2/33.3 = −0.66. Since |0.66| < 1, demand is INELASTIC.",
  catMsg:"Niko says: Midpoint formula uses the AVERAGE of old and new values as the base — that's the trick! Don't forget it! 🐈"
},
{
  id:15, topic:"Elasticity",
  text:"Mary's income increases by 10% and her demand for books decreases by 5%. Her income elasticity of demand for books is ____. Books are a(n) ____ good and ____ for Mary.",
  opts:["-0.5, inferior, a necessity","5, normal, a necessity","-2.0, normal, neither a luxury nor a necessity","0, inferior, a luxury"],
  answer:0,
  explain:"Income Elasticity = %ΔQd/%ΔIncome = −5%/10% = −0.5. NEGATIVE means it's an INFERIOR good (demand falls when income rises). Since |−0.5| < 1, it's a necessity. Think: cheap ramen — you buy less when you get richer, but it's still a staple.",
  catMsg:"Pie Cookie says: Negative = inferior good. Positive < 1 = normal necessity. Positive > 1 = luxury. Write that on your hand! 🐱"
},
{
  id:16, topic:"Elasticity",
  text:"Which demand curve is perfectly inelastic to price? (Graph shows 4 curves: 1=vertical, 2=upward sloping, 3=horizontal, 4=downward sloping)",
  opts:["2","3","1 (vertical line)","4"],
  answer:2,
  explain:"Perfectly INELASTIC = VERTICAL line (quantity doesn't change regardless of price). Think: insulin for diabetics — they need it no matter the price. Perfectly ELASTIC = HORIZONTAL (any price increase = quantity drops to zero).",
  catMsg:"Niko says: My demand for dinner is perfectly inelastic. I WILL meow at 6pm no matter what. 🐈",
  hasGraph:"inelastic"
},
{
  id:17, topic:"Trade",
  text:"Suppose the government imposes a tax on sellers. Which of the following is correct?",
  opts:["If demand were less elastic, the tax revenue would be smaller","If supply were less elastic, the tax revenue would be larger","If supply were less elastic, the deadweight loss would be larger","If demand were more elastic, the tax revenue would be larger"],
