  explain:"Less elastic supply = more vertical curve = the tax causes LESS reduction in quantity traded. So: more units still traded = LARGER tax revenue and SMALLER deadweight loss. Inelastic curves = bigger revenue rectangle, smaller DWL triangle.",
  catMsg:"Pie Cookie says: Inelastic = people (or cats) won't budge much, so the government collects more tax! 🐱"
},
{
  id:18, topic:"Trade",
  text:"Using the supply/demand graph with P_world = $50 and a quota (Q between 120 and 150): The quota restricts trade by the same amount as a tariff of:",
  opts:["$50","$30","$20","$5"],
  answer:1,
  explain:"The quota raises the domestic price from $50 (world price) to $80 (where domestic S meets restricted D). The equivalent tariff = new price − world price = $80 − $50 = $30. A $30 tariff would restrict trade by exactly the same amount.",
  catMsg:"Niko says: Quota price minus world price = the tariff twin! Simple math! 🐈"
},
{
  id:19, topic:"Trade",
  text:"Using the same quota graph (P_world=$50, quota between Q=120 and Q=150, domestic price rises to $80): The quota rent is equal to:",
  opts:["$6,400","$900","$6,000","$2,400"],
